<article>

  <p>
    Naming a hindrance is already a kind of freedom. When the mind can say
    “this is desire,” “this is restlessness,” “this is doubt” without immediately
    fighting or feeding it, something has already shifted. The
    <a href="/concepts/five-hindrances/"><span class="pali" data-pali="nīvaraṇa" data-en="hindrance">nīvaraṇas</span></a>
    page is about recognising those five qualities and meeting them with clarity.
    This page is about what comes after: the moment when one of them loosens —
    and what the mind tends to do with the gap.
  </p>

  <p>
    Dissolution is not the end of practice, and it is not a certificate. It is a
    change of conditions. How that change is met often determines whether the
    calm that follows becomes usable stillness or just another object to chase.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What Dissolution Feels Like</h2>

  <p>
    When a hindrance eases, the texture of the sit can change quickly. Desire
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="kāmacchanda" data-en="sensual desire">kāmacchanda</span>)
    that was pulling toward fantasy may simply stop pulling. Ill-will
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="byāpāda" data-en="ill-will">byāpāda</span>)
    that was reheating an old argument may cool. Dullness may lift into ordinary
    alertness. Restlessness may settle enough that the object can be held for
    more than a breath. Doubt may quiet into a willingness to keep looking.
  </p>

  <p>
    What remains is often relief — a brightness, a sudden quiet, a sense that
    there is room again. The Buddha’s water similes are useful here: dye that
    stops being stirred, boiling that stops, weeds that part, wind that dies
    down, mud that settles. The water does not become something else. It becomes
    clearer.
  </p>

  <p>
    That clarity is not the same as
    <span class="pali" data-pali="jhāna" data-en="meditative absorption">jhāna</span>.
    Absorption has its own factors and depth; a hindrance falling away is often
    only the precondition — the mind no longer blocked in that particular way.
    Nor is the relief permanent. Conditions change. What has loosened can tighten
    again. Worth holding lightly: a good sit is information about conditions, not
    proof of a new identity.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What Not to Do Next</h2>

  <p>
    The gap after a hindrance dissolves is fertile — and easily mishandled. Four
    habits show up often enough to name.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Clutching the calm.</strong> The mind notices ease and immediately
    tries to keep it. Attention turns from the meditation object to the pleasant
    absence of obstruction. The calm becomes a new form of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="kāmacchanda" data-en="sensual desire">kāmacchanda</span>
    — desire for the feeling of having dissolved desire. The grip itself tends to
    recreate agitation.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Congratulating the self.</strong> “I did it. I got past that.” A subtle
    story of ownership arrives. The hindrance was never a personal failure, and
    its passing is not a personal victory in the way the mind wants to score it.
    Ownership invites the next round of comparison and disappointment.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Hunting the next obstacle.</strong> As soon as one quality loosens,
    the mind scans for another problem to fix. The sit becomes a cleanup project.
    Useful investigation turns into restless productivity — which is close kin to
    <span class="pali" data-pali="uddhacca" data-en="restlessness">uddhacca</span>.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Interpreting as attainment.</strong> A clear patch of mind can be
    mistaken for a stage, a breakthrough, or proof that practice has finally
    “worked.” The canon is careful about this territory. Temporary absence of a
    hindrance is ordinary and valuable. It is not liberation, and treating it as
    such tends to harden into
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vicikicchā" data-en="doubt">vicikicchā</span>
    or pride when the next difficult sit arrives.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Conditions for Non-Re-Arising</h2>

  <p>
    In the
    <a href="/suttas/satipatthana/"><span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">Satipaṭṭhāna</span></a>
    formula for the hindrances, knowing that a hindrance is absent is only one
    part. The teaching also asks for knowledge of the conditions by which an
    abandoned hindrance does not arise again. That fifth knowledge is easy to
    skip in the relief of a clearer mind. It is also the one that turns a lucky
    gap into training.
  </p>

  <p>
    Practically, this does not mean forcing permanence. It means noticing what
    actually helped. Was it naming without judgment? A shift in posture or
    energy? Softening of the story that was feeding ill-will? Returning to the
    breath with less demand? The point is not to build a technique museum. It is
    to see causes and effects enough that the next arising is met earlier, with
    less identification.
  </p>

  <p>
    The tradition’s antidotes —
    <span class="pali" data-pali="asubha" data-en="unattractiveness">asubha</span>
    for desire,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="mettā" data-en="loving-kindness">mettā</span>
    for ill-will, energy for dullness, tranquility for restlessness, investigation
    for doubt — are not only for when the hindrance is roaring. They are also
    ways of protecting the gap: keeping the conditions that support clarity in
    view, without turning them into a new struggle.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    “He knows how an unarisen hindrance comes to arise; he knows how an arisen
    hindrance comes to be abandoned; he knows how an abandoned hindrance does
    not arise again in the future.”
    <cite>— MN 10, Satipaṭṭhāna Sutta (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <hr>

  <h2>Returning to the Object</h2>

  <p>
    When the obstruction loosens, the simplest instruction is often the best:
    continue the sit. Return to the breath, the body, the chosen object — not as
    a demand for more calm, but as ordinary attention in a mind that has a little
    more room. Let the gap be ordinary. Do not decorate it.
  </p>

  <p>
    If
    <span class="pali" data-pali="samādhi" data-en="unification">samādhi</span>
    deepens from there, fine. If it does not, also fine. The work at this
    threshold is not to extract a peak experience from the dissolution. It is to
    remain present while the mind is less obstructed — to see the object, the
    body, and the mind-state itself without needing the relief to become a story.
  </p>

  <p>
    Hindrances arise, are known, loosen, and return. That cycle is not a sign that
    practice has failed. It is the field in which clear seeing is trained. A mind
    that can meet the dissolving without clutching is already practicing the same
    non-grasping the path is aiming at. The water clears. Then sit with what is
    visible.
  </p>

</article>
